Objective
The objective of this experiment is:
•
to understand authentication in web applications,
•
to use Express for routing and middleware,
• to store user data in MongoDB,
• to generate and verify JWT tokens,
•
•
to secure protected routes,
and to implement login and logout flow.
Express is a minimal Node.js framework commonly used for APIs and web apps. Mongoose
provides a schema-based way to model MongoDB data. JWT is a standard for representing
claims securely between parties.
Theory
What is Authentication?
Authentication
is the process of verifying the identity of a user.
When a user logs in with valid credentials, the server confirms who the user is.
What is Authorization?
Authorization
decides what an authenticated user is allowed to access.
For example, only logged-in users should be allowed to view protected pages.
What is JWT?
JWT (JSONWebToken)
is a compact token format used to securely transmit information between parties. After
successful login, the server can issue a signed token, and later verify that token on protected
requests.
Why use MongoDB?
MongoDB is used to store user details such as:
•
username
•
email
•
hashed password
MongoDB can be accessed from Node.js directly with the official driver, and Mongoose is a
popular ODM layer on top of MongoDB for schemas and models.
Logout with JWT
JWT is usually stateless. So, logout commonly means:
•
removing the token from the client side, or
•
maintaining a token blacklist in advanced systems
For a simple lab experiment, clearing the stored token on the client side is enough.
